    <div>
      <h2 style="margin-bottom: 0;">Use Cases</h2>
      <p>The Fluid Head is built with the “big-eye” hunter in mind. The type of hunter that uses this head likes to get a commanding view of a large piece of country. We’re talking BTX 115, Kowa Highlander guys. This tripod head is rated for the weight of about 10 sets of Highlanders, so you’ll never have to worry whether it can deal with that kind of stress.</p>
      <p>The pan and tilt functions on this head are simple, intuitive, and customizable to your style. Each lever has the ability to cam, and the knobs are made of solid, machined aluminum to match the strength of the body. They’re also oversized, so you’ll never miss an opportunity on a cold day that requires gloves.</p>
      <p>The handle is shorter than most video heads because when you glass, you’re nice and tight to the head. This gives you the option to run the handle forward or backward without reaching way forward or back to manipulate it. The main reason that most video heads include a 16”+ handle is to create the illusion of smoothness. The Fluid Head is really just that smooth.</p>
      <p>When paired with an extended plate or Balance Rail, Shop Manager Joe Mannino describes the glassing experience with one word – “Sublime.” It truly is a level of smoothness and balance that we’ve never seen in any other tripod head.</p>
      <p>The best part? It’s just as spectacular to use this head with binoculars. Now, with the new Combo Jaws set for the Fluid Head, you can easily switch between a spotter and binoculars without changing any plates–it’s machined for both. Ryan, our in-house coues deer magician, can sometimes be found using both at the same time. We don’t recommend it, but it’s possible.</p>
